ive Complexities of the Film Musical Exemplified by Lars von Trier’s Dancer in the Dark (2000) -- tThe Unnatural in E. A. Poe’s “The Oval Portrait” -- tPostmodernist Impossibilities, the Creation of New Cognitive Frames, and Attempts at Interpretation -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays looks at two important manifestations of postclassical narratology, namely transmedial narratology on the one hand, and unnatural narratology on the other. The articles deal with films, graphic novels, computer games, web series, the performing arts, journalism, reality games, music, musicals, and the representation of impossibilities. The essays demonstrate how new media and genres as well as unnatural narratives challenge classical forms of narration in ways that call for the development of analytical tools and modelling systems that move beyond classical structuralist narratology. The articles thus contribute to the further development of both transmedial and unnatural narrative theory, two of the most important manifestations of postclassical narratology.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aMass media and language. 0aMass media. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aStorytelling in mass media. 4aErzähltheorie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aNarrative theory.  afilm studies.  aliterary studies.  amedia studies.1 aAlber, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlber, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerning, Nora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrütsch, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEls